description.text:
Update: Added 2 slot and 4 slot OPTIONAL extenders so you can make these as tall as you dare. :)

I decided to remix the Pen holder for 13.4mm and 8 Sharpie Pens (instead of 16). This should also fit the thin expo white board markers. Printed fine on my MP Prusa i3.

Suggested Print process:

Print the "DNA_Helix_Sharpie_Pen_Holder_13mm_BothParts02.stl" STL file
After print, remove two parts from print bed.
a. bottom of helix is outer print
b. top of helix is inner print.
Assemble with glue, or your favorite adhesive to make the bond permanent. (I used super glue).
Insert Pens and display.

Optional Extender Instructions: (For those with more pens and/or just want to go taller)

  1. Print the original file "DNA_Helix_Sharpie_Pen_Holder_13mm_BothParts02"
  2. Pick either the 2 or 4 slot extender design and print a pair for each level you want to add.
  3. The 4 slot extender is going to be a challenging print. I suggest hairspray or glue stick or whatever trick you use to stick a design that tends to lean. If you are having problems with the taller 4 slot design, switch to using 2 sets of the 2 slot design (easier to print).
  4. After printing these, they should fit between the top and bottom parts of the original print design. Use super or krazy glue to make permanent.
  5. Another benefit of the extenders is that you can make the design more colorful by printing in different filament shades.

I also have a pencil version here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1803253

description.text:
This wheel balancer that I have designed myself and have the two main essential black pieces 3-D printed out at one of my local hobby shops, and for the handle I bought PVC pipe from a hardware store to cut down on costs and I also needed to bearings hex nut
and i need one front axle form a RC vehicle but I purchase the spare parts themselves and used one of them to build this device. If you decide to download this file you will need

  1. You will need 1/2"2 PVC pipe can get them at a hardware store of your choice.

  2. You will also need four screws this rules must be 3x23mm

  3. You will need one front axles from traxxas part no.3637

  4. You will need one hex nut from traxxas part no.3654

  5. You will need two bearings from traxxas part no.5116

  6. You will need one pin part no.2754

So now I will go ahead and explain to you how to assemble it. In one of the photos
you see one of the two 3-D printed parts behind it is the bearings, hex nuts, and the front axle.
So we will go ahead and assembled this part of the wheel balancer.

In the next photo you see the same parts behind it is the dremel power tool infront of it are some bits to be used with the dremel power tool. Why depending upon your 3-D printer you will have to do some dremeling (sanding)to get some of the rough edges out and to remove the excess out of the area where the bearings are going to be fitted in.

After you are done with the dremeling (sanding) you will begin to fit in the bearings as you see in one of the photos where I just dremel out the excess to help fit in the bearings better. And also in one of the photos you will place the bearing on the other side of this part of the wheel balancer as well.

In the next photo you should get and idea how it should look like after you placed in the bearings in this parts
of the wheel balancer.

After you are done you will go ahead and insert one of the axles into the backside of this parts of the wheel balancer. As you see here in the photos on how I did that.

after you are Done with the assembly it should look like this as you see here in one of the photos.

In the next set of photos you will insert a pin on to the hole on the axle as you see here in the photos and you should get the and results in the next photo.

Then the next thing you will do is to insert the hex nut as you see here in one of the photos.

And then after that it should look like this as you see here in one of the photos.

So after you are done with that you are going to take the 3-D printed bigger part of this wheel balancer and use the dremel to sand out some of the excess so you will be able to fit the 3-D printed part on to the PVC pipe.

After you got that done do a test fit to make sure everything fits in correctly. If not
do some more sanding.

After you're done with that as you see here in one of the photos decide how much link that you want for the handle and then cut the PVC pipe to the link that you want.

After getting the PVC pipe cut to size done as you see in one of the photos the parts
now ready to be assembled.

As you see here in one of the photos is the PVC pipe the other 3-D printed parts with the
the 3/4"1/2 PVC Male adapter I am using this part because I wanted to upgrade this
wheel balancer later. But not necessary but would help.

So what I did here in one of the photos I installed the PVC male adapter onto the
PVC pipe itself and then you superglue to glue it in place.

The next thing I did is to get the paint job not necessary but I did it because
I want this to look good.

After getting that done I have to sand some of the excess paint off of the PVC pipe
so I can fit the 3-D printed part in.

After getting that done I you superglue to secure this 3-D printed part on to the PVC pipe
as you see here in one of the photos.

After getting that done you will start inserting the screws in to the first part
of this wheel balancer that involves the bearings and front axle that has been assembled
earlier.

The next thing you will do is to insert the screws through the holes as you see in the photos
on where to put the screws in as you see here in one of the photos.

Then the next thing you will do is just to screw this part onto the handle itself

After that the wheel balancer should be completely assembled as you see here in the photos.

Then the next thing you will do is take one of your wheels and test it out to make sure
that everything works so now you can go and balancer wheels with out blowing a lot of money so enjoy

description.text: made with tinkercad

I don't especially enjoy the idea of soldering 225 LEDs together to make a display, so here is a simple solution that I used to avoid cutting and soldering these lights.

This is a minimal system with two parts that combine to make sturdy plastic cubicles for your DIY LED display.

These partitions are spaced for the 30 LEDs/Meter strips such as the WS281** sold as NeoPixels or similar. The ones that I used for this project were the waterproof type that have a sticky back. IP65?

I printed my partitions out 5 at a time without a raft and 30% infill. Depending on the opacity of your filament, you may want to adjust this accordingly.

The partitions came out a little warped so I made the corner connector piece to stabilize the structure for mounting. I think those who print with rafts or different printers might not need as many of these corner things; I used about 25.

remixed_from.title: Alternate fan mount system for Sparkcube XL

description.text:
This is a remix of the "Alternate fan mount system" found here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1734379

Because I use the original Sparkcube X-carriage, I redesigned the fan mount plate.
You can easily adjust the height of the plate to match the length of your hotend.
I use 2 x 50mm radial fan (blower fan)

I use a E3D Lite6 and it is mounted underneath the X-carriage. For cooling the hotend, I use a 40mm fan (fanduct can be found on thingiverse).

You can use the fan duct of the origin thing or use one of the attached fan ducts. Because the initial fan duct seems to be too short for my hotend, I designed different variants. Also I increased the height of the fan duct mount flag.

  1. Sparkcube_Radial_Fan_duct_long_wide_23mm is a longer version, the inner distance of tubes is 23mm. It is very close to the heater block of E3D Lite6-
  2. Sparkcube_Radial_Fan_duct_long_wide_30mm is also a longer version, but the space between the tubes is 30mm wide.
  3. Sparkcube_Radial_Fan_duct_30mm is a ring cooler with an internal diameter of approx. 30mm
  4. Sparkcube_Radial_Fan_duct_30mm_incr_gap has the same size than the 30mm ring version. But the gap where the air exits is small at beginning and larger at the end (see drawings)
  5. Sparkcube_Radial_Fan_duct_40mm is another ring cooler with an internal diameter of approx 40mm. This fits good around my heater block
  6. Sparkcube_Radial_Fan_duct_40mm_flat has the same dimensions like 40mm versions, but the tube is more flat. This was necessary to me because my 40mm fan mount collids with the fan duct 5.

Assembly:

  • First print Sparkcube_Radial_Fan_mount file and one of the fan duct files.
  • Unscrew the sparkcube hotend cooler, use the screws of it to attach the mounting plate on X-carriage
  • Attach your blower fans. Use a hand drill to create holes where you need them (there are different versions of blower fans out there)
  • Attach the fan duct by just press the blower fan tubes into the fan duct.
  • Use screws or a zip tie to fix the fan duct. Just drill a hole on the "flag" part of fan duct. At fast moves, the fan duct may fall off so please fix it as described.

UPDATE:

  • 2016-12-06: 40mm fan duct versions are now more strong and are easier to print.

This is a model of a Geneva Drive, which converts continuous rotational motion to intermittent continuous motion.. (think of the seconds hand on a clock which "ticks" rather than moving smoothly). http://youtu.be/HCnYnhws_cA

Print the base and then one of each wheel (either printing each wheel independently or use the bothwheels file). The wheel with the finger-hole (wheel one) goes finger-hole side up, The other wheel (with the spikes) goes upside down.

title: Lasercut OpenTheremin v.3 case with 3d printing version

description.text:
This is a lasercut case for OpenTheremin v3 musical instrument by Urs Gaudens (www.gaudi.ch). You will have to cut 6 OpenTheremin_case_3 parts and 1 each of the others.
I used 3mm acrylic except one middle layer where antennas connectors go - this is a 5mm acrylic. For assembly I used four m3x35 screws.
I also provide an .stl file if someone wants to 3d-print this case; then you have all the .dxf files to create an i/o, top (with text and without) and bottom panels. Thickness should be 3mm.

comments.text: I just completed assembly and it looks great!  Thanks so much.  I did have to modify the files a bit.  I don't know if they changed the board slightly after you designed your case, but the OpenTheremin board I received is slightly too long for the box.  I had to modify OpenTheremin_case_3_5mm to slim down the top part.  Also the openings for the controls and LEDs were 3.5mm too low.  The bottom edge of the board is flush with IO_panel_OpenTheremin so it isn't just a matter of the whole board shifting up by a bit.  The laser at the Makerspace was treating each straight line as a single vector instead of grouping them into a path.  This increased the cutting time tremendously.  I used Inkscape to create new files and that really sped it up.  Thank you for providing a blank cover.  I liked the look of the board so I used a piece of clear plexi for the top and engraved a custom message since this is a Christmas gift.
comments.author: Oahu_Makerspace

comments.text:
I measured everything accurately, and it all fits. There is a cut in IO_panel_OpenTheremin, and protruding bit of the PCB should go there - this describes your offset of 3.5mm (but then the rest of the PCB will not fit!). Thickness of the OpenTheremin_case_3_5mm is 5mm because this part goes level with antenna connectors - and they are 5mm thick.
As for the laser at Makerspace - I am using a chinese laser engraver/cutter with modified control unit (AWC608), and haven't experienced any problem with shapes being treated as a single vector; you can try Group command in your CAD software. Without an information which laser cutter is at the Makerspace and what software it uses I cannot really tell.
comments.author: Oahu_Makerspace

comments.text: Now that is interesting.  I removed the cut in the IO_panel_OpenTheremin because it looked like a mistake.  It touched the USB  and the headphone jack openings but it wasn't connected to them on a vector level.  Having the OpenTheremin board stick out through the opening would make sense and everything would shift down and fit.  It would have also addressed the modification I had to do to get the Arduino to fit. But looking at my assembly, then the antenna posts would be too low.  Hmm.
comments.author: nd595

comments.text: just take a good fine cutters and trim the protruding things on your arduino - they are made without any attention to the tolerances. Everything there does fit, and I measured things tightly; you will see that it does work. Also, as I did not have right tools, I made a holes in the bottom panel diameter 2.1; then using the m2.5x35 they did cut the thread required, and I did not need the nuts (and I did not have a longer screws). In any case glad to know your receiver enjoys it - the greatest pleasure in life is to share!
comments.author: Oahu_Makerspace

comments.text:
There is no open wiring there, all the circuits are on Arduino Uno and Open Theremin PCB. Because all versions of Open Theremin cases by Gaudi on thingiverse are for the older versions, I just made this simple case for the V.3. If you decide to go the 3D-printing route, there are two technological holes for making the antenna connectors attached to the instrument PCB. Antennas are made from the aluminium tubes with 4mm inner diameter.
An external connections are through USB connector for power (or one could use the +5V connector on the Arduino) and sound output minijack. They are covered by IO panel with a cutout for the main PCB. Simple.

A cookie cutter for Saint Patrick's Day.

Scale it down if required, this is about as big as could fit on my ABP. Print with 100% fill. Use green for St. Patrick's day. Use it to make cookies or play-dough cut-outs. The design is from the shamrock on Wikimedia Commons. http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Shamrock.svg To create the cookie cutter I converted it to three DXF files. One as-is, two as a path insets, and one as a path outset. The OpenSCAD file shows how the outset forms the base and the insets make it hollow. The first version had walls that were too think, so I decreased the amount of inset for shamrockinset2.dxf. If you'd like thicker walls, in shamrock.scad replace the shamrockinset2.dxf with shamrockinset1.dxf. I did actually print it in green, the camera just made it look blueish.

description.text: Model plane

Halloween was approaching, and I’d been invited to a few parties so needed to come up with something.
Somehow the idea of a blowfly seemed appealing as I’d never seen a mask like that before, and making something with large compound eyes seemed like a blast.

The design only took a few hours. it was made from primitives in Autodesk123D then taken to Meshmixer for textures, hollowing and smoothing. If you haven’t used Meshmixer it’s almost like a 3D pain program that allows you to build, smooth, subtract and texture basic models.

Printing was very straight forward with supports used for the face/nose section but not for the eyes. I was in a bit of a rush so printed them at 80mm/s at 0.2mm layer heights.

The sections were then melted into position from behind with a hot soldering iron and the gaps filled with epoxy glue. It was then a matter of painting everything black with water based acrylic paints. After the black had dried I applied a coat of deep red using a sponge, the idea here was that the groves between the bumps on the eyes would stay dark. I then applied some purple (the only reddish colour I had) pearlescent paint over the surface with a sponge to give it that glint.

The fur on the face was a little tricky. I had a piece of black fake fur from an off-cuts bin, so i chopped the fibers from the backing and attached them to the face using a thick layer of black acrylic paint, once I was happy with the effect I sprayed over it with fixative to keep it all in place. The fur around the edges was simply a strip of feather trim from the sewing shop hot glued on, and the whiskers are made of necklace string.

The wings were simple enough to design, I simply found some macro images of fly wings through google images, touched them up in Photoshop, converted them into vectors using illustrator, then exported them as .dxf files, expanded them in Fusion360, then smoothed and manipulated them in mesh mixer.

each wing is printed in 3 pieces, a white wing sandwiched between two sets of black wing veins. I simply epoxy glued the veins onto the wings and using black acrylic paint covered the edges of the wings where the layers were visible.

The two finished wings are then epoxy glued into a center piece which I covered with fur using the same method as the mask.

I made the mounting plate as a separate piece that screwed onto the wing assembly so that it could be easily replaced if broken. The elastics are just flat 12mm elastics which are stitched into position. I used a small bag clip scaled to 45% which I’d downloaded from thingiverse to join the elastics, but I realized afterwards that the clips weren’t needed as there was plenty of stretch for me to get my arms through it.

The costume turned out pretty well, and I even won a prize for my efforts

description.text:
We have recreated the Magical Shield from the first Zelda game, appeared for the Nintendo Entertainment System in 1986.

It is designed with two goals in mind: a nice ornament for fans and an easy design that doesn't require many hours of printing/money.

All the elements of this shield are designed to be printed quickly, spray painted and finally glued on a flat surface of wood, agglomerate or plywood.

Since it does not weigh too much, it can be glued on flat surfaces with double-sided adhesive tape. You can also frame it and place it on the wall as if it were a picture to decorate your video game room.

This design was inspired by the wonderful Blue Amnesiac's Illustration available at blueamnesiac.deviantart.com.

If you liked, a small tip will help us continue to share new ideas. Thank you!

Hemos recreado el Magical Shield de Link del primer juego de la saga The Legend of Zelda, aparecido para NES en 1986.

Está diseñado con dos objetivos en mente: un bonito adorno para fans y un diseño fácil que no requiera muchas horas de impresión y dinero.

Todos los elementos de este escudo están pensados para ser impresos rápidamente, pintar con spray y finalmente pegados sobre una superficie plana de madera, aglomerado o contrachapado.

Como no pesa demasiado, se puede pegar sobre superficies planas con cinta adhesiva de doble cara. También se puede enmarcar y colocarlo en la pared como si se tratara de un cuadro para adornar una sala de videojuegos.

Diseño inspirado en la maravillosa ilustración de Blue Amnesiac disponible en blueamnesiac.deviantart.com.

Si te ha gustado, una pequeña propina nos ayudará a seguir compartiendo nuevas ideas. ¡Gracias!

description.text:
This bobbin was designed to fit the S10 Spinning wheel. This is a bobbin driven wheel with the drive wheel moving the bobbin, and the flyer attached to a brake.

To build this, print out both ends. Attach them to a piece of PEX tube. You can get the PEX water pipes from HomeDepot for a few bucks. The material is soft, and can be cut with a sharp knife.

I recommend using glue to attach the PEX to the bobbin ends.

Printer:

Prusa I3

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

No

Infill:

40%

Notes:

The whorl is upside down. Please flip it over so that the largest pulley is flat on the print bed.

The opposite end (non-whorl) can be printed either way, but I recommend flipping it so that the small hole is on the bottom, and the larger hole is on top. The Slicer may require supports if you print it large hole on bottom.

To finish the project, you will need a short piece of 1/2" PEX or similar water pipe. CPVC may also work depending on the size. Insert it into the large holes on each end of the parts. Be sure to use glue. I recommend using general purpose Gorilla Glue, or SuperGlue.

You can obtain the PEX water pipes from most home improvement stores. I was able to source it at Home Depot. They sell "repair" pieces for about $3. They are about 2 feet long. I was able to build several bobbins using a single piece.

title: Z Lathe CNC easy mount Jet BD7 Nema 17

description.text:
It's Update for http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1918647

Today, it was necessary to cut a thread. So I updated Z motor mount.
Same motor nema 17.

You will need:

  1. M5x30 bolt.
  2. M5 nut.
  3. The fastening strip. I made it from the aluminum strip width of 10mm and 2mm thick. The drawing can be seen on photo.
    (However, you can print it. STL file enhanced version I attached (it is the bolt with the Allen)).

The same motor mount type.

Advice

  1. I propose to drill a hole for the lubrication of plain bearing on lead screw. You can see it on photo.
  2. Drill a hole for the lubrication of plain bearing on the other side of the lead screw.
  3. Adjust the position of the screw shaft. It must be turning by hand.
    The best thing - you can close all the standard cover of the machine.

title: Headphone Screw Clamp Holder

description.text:
First design I've made from scratch as a means of learning Fusion 360.

Dimensions

The clamp max height for a desk is around 34mm without the bolt. Using the bolt, it can clamp on to a desk as thin as 11mm. I moved the bolt back to hopefully avoid fatigue on the joint.

Files

Aside from the bolt file, I included 3 clamp STL files.

  • Clamp A: Includes the words "headphones" and "portablesheep" on the design.
  • Clamp B: Only includes the word "headphones" on the design.
  • Clamp C: Omits all words from the design.

Credit to the design that I modeled this after: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1657541

Printer:

Monoprice Maker v2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Resolution:

2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I printed this on a glass bed, with 20% infill, and at medium quality.

I slowed down my outline print speeds though, just to ensure the threading came out clean. So if you're having issues with the threading, try slowing down the outline and possibly infill.

I used supports, but only from the built platform. They can cause some etching issues on the final print when done from the side, but nothing bad.
